Global cannabis suppliers struggled to keep up with demand on Saturday, the biggest ever 4/20 Day, an annual celebration of marijuana on 20 April, which in the US calendar is referred to as 4/20. Suppliers in the US, where recreational cannabis is legal in 10 states, and Canada, where the drug was decriminalised for recreational use last year, reported difficulties fulfilling orders on what has been called the industryâ€™s Black Friday. Some delivery websites, and the biggest legal delivery app, Eaze, crashed under the weight of demand on Saturday. Online cannabis dispensaries Nugg and Chill also suffered difficulties throughout the day. Eaze crashed repeatedly soon after it began â€œhappy hourâ€, with free delivery in California, and a 20% discount on cannabis-related products in other states. âœ¨Itâ€™s Happy Hour. âœ¨Free delivery. ğŸ¥³9am - 2pm PST. â€œWe know Eaze.com is experiencing intermittent outages and have all hands on deck working to keep up with demand,â€ the company said on Twitter. â€œThank you for your patience.â€ â€œThe volume was unprecedented - cannabis has definitely gone mainstream,â€ an Eaze spokeswoman said. â€œThe lines to dispensaries across California were out the door.â€ A spokesperson for the Canadian government said: â€œHealth Canada is aware of reports of localised shortages of cannabis products in some markets and for some product lines.â€ Armen Yemenidjian, the chief executive of Essence Cannabis Dispensaries, which is based in Las Vegas, said 20 April was â€œdefinitely the Black Friday of the industryâ€, in reference to the day in November that has become the busiest shopping day of the year. â€œIt also pays homage to the culture that has moved the cannabis industry forward for the past couple of decades,â€ he said in an interview with the Las Vegas Sun. â€œ4/20 has been adopted by the mainstream and used as a symbol for cannabis.â€ The annual celebration, which dates to the 1990s, has been hijacked by big brands seeking to cash in. 